# Pattern Evaluation - LCP-UML-9 (2026-03-23)

- Total classes/records inspected: 13 (5 controllers, 8 request/DTO records)
- Patterns found (unique): 5 — Dependency Injection, Transaction Script, Unit of Work (EF DbContext), Optimistic Concurrency (row version tokens), Data Transfer Object
- Pattern density: 5 / 13 = 0.38
- Overall grade: D+ (controllers are thin wrappers over EF Core with DI and concurrency safeguards, but they bypass domain/services, expose persistence concerns, and lack interface-driven abstraction; SRP/ISP/ DIP mostly unmet).

| Component | Kind | Patterns Observed | Abstract/Concrete | Notes on SOLID & Coupling |
| --- | --- | --- | --- | --- |
| IdentityRegistriesController | Controller | DI; Transaction Script; Unit of Work (DbContext transaction) | Concrete | Direct EF queries/transactions inside controller couples API to persistence; no interface or domain service; SRP/DIP weak. |
| PassportServicesController | Controller | DI; Transaction Script; Unit of Work; Optimistic Concurrency | Concrete | Handles transactions and concurrency in controller; lacks service/repository abstraction; logic mixed with transport layer. |
| DriversLicensesController | Controller | DI; Transaction Script; Optimistic Concurrency | Concrete | Update logic and EF tracking in controller; no validation/service boundary; tightly coupled to DbContext. |
| VotingRegistriesController | Controller | DI; Transaction Script; Optimistic Concurrency | Concrete | Persistence and business rules embedded; no separation of concerns; concurrency handled correctly. |
| AuditTrailsController | Controller | DI; Transaction Script; Unit of Work | Concrete | Creates audit entries in controller; transaction started directly; no domain encapsulation. |
| PersonDto | Record (DTO) | Data Transfer Object | Concrete | Simple DTO; no validation; used directly by controller; fine for boundary. |
| CreateIdentityRegistryRequest | Record (DTO) | Data Transfer Object | Concrete | Request model; no mapping layer; controllers mutate domain directly. |
| UpdateIdentityRegistryRequest | Record (DTO) | Data Transfer Object | Concrete | Same as above; thin contract. |
| CreatePassportServiceRequest | Record (DTO) | Data Transfer Object | Concrete | DTO without validation; coupled to entity fields. |
| UpdatePassportServiceRequest | Record (DTO) | Data Transfer Object | Concrete | DTO; concurrency token enforced by controller. |
| UpdateDriversLicenseRequest | Record (DTO) | Data Transfer Object | Concrete | DTO; mapped manually in controller. |
| UpdateVotingRegistryRequest | Record (DTO) | Data Transfer Object | Concrete | DTO; mapped manually in controller. |
| CreateAuditTrailRequest | Record (DTO) | Data Transfer Object | Concrete | DTO used directly inside controller transaction. |

## Gaps & Risks
- No domain entity implementations or repository/service layers present; controllers talk directly to "'`AppDbContext`, making persistence concerns leak across the API.
- No abstractions/interfaces for data access or domain policies; Dependency Inversion violated and unit testing difficult without heavy mocks of EF Core.
- Validation and business rules are minimal; transactions are started per action but without domain invariants, risking inconsistent state.
- Missing implementations for Domain/Infrastructure folders (only empty directories), suggesting incomplete architecture and broken layering.

## Improvement Suggestions
1) Introduce application services and repositories (interfaces + implementations) to move transaction/EF logic out of controllers and satisfy DIP/ISP.
2) Add domain entities/value objects with behavior plus validators; controllers should map DTOs to commands handled by the application layer.
3) Centralize concurrency and transaction handling in a unit-of-work service/decorator rather than per-controller code to reduce duplication.
4) Add automated tests around transaction boundaries and concurrency conflicts once the abstractions exist.
